A.1 - Prerequisites for practical test
	•	Confirms the applicant’s checkride prep is recent, not stale.
	•	Helps ensure oral knowledge and flight skills are still current on test day.
	•	Shows the instructor believes the applicant is truly ready to be evaluated.

A.2 - Review of deficiencies identified on airman knowledge test
	•	Makes sure missed written-test topics were reviewed before the checkride.
	•	Helps fix weak areas like airspace, weather, or regulations before testing.
	•	Reduces the chance the same knowledge gaps show up during the oral.

A.3 - Pre-solo aeronautical knowledge
	•	Proves the student understands the aircraft, rules, and local procedures before flying alone.
	•	Helps confirm the student knows emergency actions and operating limits.
	•	Prevents a first solo from happening before the student has the needed knowledge base.

A.4 - Pre-solo flight training
	•	Shows the student can safely control the airplane without the instructor onboard.
	•	Confirms the student can handle takeoffs, landings, go-arounds, and pattern work.
	•	Gives the instructor a documented basis for allowing solo flight.

A.5 - Pre-solo flight training at night
	•	Night flying is harder because of reduced visual cues and common illusions.
	•	Helps ensure the student knows runway lighting, night procedures, and night judgment.
	•	The 90-day limit keeps that night training recent.

A.6 - Solo flight (first 90-calendar-day period)
	•	This is the student’s main legal authority for first solo flight.
	•	Limits the solo to the specific make and model the student was trained in.
	•	The 90-day limit forces regular instructor oversight.

A.7 - Solo flight (each additional 90-calendar-day period)
	•	Prevents solo privileges from continuing indefinitely without review.
	•	Lets the instructor recheck the student’s skill, judgment, and consistency.
	•	Helps catch rust or bad habits before more solo flying.

A.8 - Solo takeoffs and landings at another airport within 25 NM
	•	Allows another nearby airport only after instructor approval.
	•	Helps account for different runways, traffic, radio workload, and layouts.
	•	Keeps the student from expanding solo operations without supervision.

A.9 - Solo cross-country flight
	•	Confirms the student got the training needed before leaving the local area alone.
	•	Covers more than flying skill, including planning, navigation, weather, and fuel.
	•	Establishes the student is ready for solo XC operations in that aircraft.

A.10 - Solo cross-country flight
	•	Requires instructor review for each specific solo XC flight.
	•	Lets the instructor check route, weather, fuel, performance, and decision-making.
	•	Prevents a student from launching on an unsafe or poorly planned trip.

A.11 - Repeated solo cross-country flights not more than 50 NM from the point of departure
	•	Makes repeated short solo routes easier to authorize and manage.
	•	Keeps the route limited and familiar rather than open-ended.
	•	Works well for repeated training flights between known airports.

A.12 - Solo flight in Class B airspace
	•	Class B is high-workload airspace with heavy traffic and tighter ATC expectations.
	•	Confirms the student received special training for that environment.
	•	The 90-day limit keeps that approval current.

A.13 - Solo flight to, from, or at an airport located in Class B airspace
	•	A Class B airport can be more demanding than just entering Class B airspace.
	•	Helps ensure the student can handle taxi complexity, sequencing, and faster traffic.
	•	Prevents solo operations at major airports without specific approval.

A.14 - Endorsement of U.S. citizenship recommended by the Transportation Security Administration (TSA)
	•	Documents that citizenship verification was completed when using the endorsement method.
	•	Helps the instructor show compliance with TSA flight training security requirements.
	•	Protects both instructor and student if records are later reviewed.

A.15 - Solo flight in Class B, C, and D airspace
	•	Controlled airspace adds traffic, radio work, and sequencing demands.
	•	Confirms a sport or recreational student was specifically trained for that environment.
	•	The 90-day limit requires recent review of those skills.

A.16 - Solo flight to, from, or at an airport located in Class B, C, or D airspace or at an airport having an operational control tower
	•	Towered airport operations require accurate communication and instruction compliance.
	•	Helps ensure the student can handle taxi, hold short, runway entries, and pattern flow.
	•	Reduces the risk of confusion in busy airport environments.

A.17 - Aeronautical knowledge test
	•	Shows the applicant was prepared before taking the written test.
	•	Helps prevent poor test attempts based on weak or incomplete study.
	•	Creates a record that required ground prep was completed.

A.18 - Taking flight proficiency check for different category or class of aircraft
	•	Confirms the pilot is ready to be evaluated for a new category or class.
	•	Recognizes that moving to a different category or class can involve major differences.
	•	Helps ensure the pilot does not test before receiving the needed training.

A.19 - Passing flight proficiency check for different category or class of aircraft
	•	Records that the pilot completed the required training and proficiency for that added privilege.
	•	Creates a clear qualification record, not just informal familiarization.
	•	Supports the FAA basis for granting the new privilege.

A.20 - Taking sport pilot practical test
	•	Shows the applicant was trained to practical-test level, not just basic familiarity.
	•	Acts as the instructor’s formal recommendation to test.
	•	Helps the examiner receive a prepared applicant.

A.21 - Passing a sport pilot practical test
	•	Documents that the required training and proficiency standard were met.
	•	Supports the certification record after successful testing.
	•	Shows the outcome is tied to documented preparation, not just test-day performance.

A.22 - Passing a sport pilot practical test with a simplified flight controls limitation
	•	Connects the qualification to the specific aircraft/control configuration used.
	•	Helps match the pilot’s privilege to the proper limitation or authorization.
	•	Ensures the paperwork reflects the actual basis of qualification.

A.23 - Class B, C, or D airspace; at an airport located in Class B, C, or D airspace; or to, from, through, or at an airport having an operational control tower
	•	Shows the pilot was trained for more complex airspace and airport operations.
	•	Covers communication, sequencing, and traffic-management demands.
	•	Prevents higher-workload operations without specific training.

A.24 - Aircraft that has a maximum speed in level flight with maximum continuous power (VH) less than or equal to 87 KCAS
	•	Separates lower-performance aircraft from faster ones.
	•	Recognizes that slower airplanes usually allow more time for planning and correction.
	•	Helps tie training and privilege level to aircraft performance.

A.25 - Aircraft that has a VH greater than 87 KCAS
	•	Faster aircraft increase workload and reduce reaction time.
	•	Pilots need stronger energy management and earlier planning in higher-speed airplanes.
	•	Helps prevent pilots from treating faster aircraft like basic trainers.

A.26 - Flight training at night
	•	Night flying includes different risks than daytime flying.
	•	Helps cover illusions, reduced visual references, and lighting systems.
	•	Builds safer judgment for night departures, arrivals, and navigation.

A.27 - To act as pilot in command (PIC) in an aircraft with retractable landing gear
	•	Retractable gear adds systems management and checklist discipline.
	•	Helps prevent common and costly errors like gear-up landings.
	•	Confirms the pilot can manage the added complexity safely.

A.28 - To act as PIC in an airplane with a manual controllable pitch propeller
	•	Manual propeller control changes engine and performance management.
	•	The pilot must understand how settings affect climb, cruise, and descent.
	•	Prevents misuse by pilots trained only in fixed-pitch trainers.

A.29 - Aeronautical knowledge test
	•	Creates a record that the applicant was academically prepared before testing.
	•	Helps ensure the written exam measures learning, not guesswork.
	•	Supports instructor accountability for ground preparation.

A.30 - Flight proficiency/practical test
	•	Serves as the instructor’s formal statement that the applicant is ready to test.
	•	Helps screen out applicants with unresolved skill or judgment problems.
	•	Supports the integrity of the practical-test process.

A.31 - Recreational pilot to operate within 50 NM of the airport where training was received
	•	Keeps the pilot’s operating area tied to a familiar training environment.
	•	Recognizes that local knowledge matters for a limited-privilege pilot.
	•	Prevents routine operation beyond the area the pilot was trained for.

A.32 - Recreational pilot to act as PIC on a flight that exceeds 50 NM of the departure airport
	•	Going farther requires stronger navigation, weather, and diversion planning.
	•	Confirms the pilot got training beyond basic local-area use.
	•	Helps manage the added risk of unfamiliar airports and longer routes.

A.33 - Recreational pilot with less than 400 flight hours and no logged PIC time within the preceding 180 calendar days
	•	Low total time plus low recent time can raise risk significantly.
	•	Helps refresh skill and judgment before acting on pilot privileges again.
	•	Adds oversight when rust may be a major factor.

A.34 - Recreational pilot to conduct solo flights for the purpose of obtaining an additional certificate or rating while under the supervision of an authorized flight instructor
	•	Allows needed solo experience while still keeping the operation supervised.
	•	Supports training toward a new certificate or rating without assuming full qualification.
	•	Gives structure and limits during a transition phase.

A.35 - Class B, C, or D airspace; at an airport located in Class B, C, or D airspace; or to, from, through, or at an airport having an operational control tower
	•	Requires specific preparation before entering more demanding airspace or towered airports.
	•	Focuses on communication, sequencing, and traffic awareness.
	•	Helps keep limited-privilege pilots out of complex environments unless trained.

A.36 - Aeronautical knowledge test
	•	Confirms the applicant completed required ground prep before testing.
	•	Helps improve test readiness and consistency.
	•	Provides a documented training record for that test path.

A.37 - Flight proficiency/practical test
	•	Shows the applicant reached test-level proficiency, not just lesson completion.
	•	Supports the instructor’s decision to recommend the applicant.
	•	Helps protect the practical-test process from premature applicants.

A.38 - Aeronautical knowledge test
	•	Provides the same check on academic readiness for another certificate or rating path.
	•	Helps ensure the applicant has the required knowledge foundation.
	•	Keeps training records complete and consistent.

A.39 - Flight proficiency/practical test
	•	Documents readiness for evaluation under that certificate or rating path.
	•	Shows the applicant was screened by an instructor before testing.
	•	Helps align training completion with FAA evaluation standards.

A.40 - Restricted privileges ATP Certificate, Airplane Multiengine Land (AMEL) rating
	•	Restricted ATP pathways have strict eligibility rules that must be documented.
	•	Connects the applicant to the correct ATP route and standard.
	•	Helps ensure the certificate is issued under the proper authority and basis.

A.41 - ATP Certification Training Program (CTP)
	•	ATP-level operations require knowledge beyond typical GA training.
	•	Covers advanced topics like high-altitude operations, systems, and transport-style concepts.
	•	Creates a common baseline before ATP written testing.

A.42 - Aeronautical knowledge test
	•	Confirms the applicant was prepared for the ATP-level written exam.
	•	Supports testing in more advanced subject areas than lower certificates require.
	•	Helps ensure the applicant did not skip formal academic preparation.

A.43 - Flight proficiency/practical test
	•	Documents readiness for ATP-level evaluation.
	•	Supports the applicant’s eligibility for one of the highest certification levels.
	•	Helps show the applicant was trained to a polished, professional standard.

A.44 - Prerequisites for instrument practical tests
	•	Instrument flying depends on precise procedures and solid judgment.
	•	Combines recent checkride prep with review of written-test weak areas.
	•	The 2-calendar-month limit keeps instrument skills and knowledge fresh.

A.45 - Fundamentals of instructing knowledge test
	•	Good flying skill does not automatically mean good teaching skill.
	•	FOI builds the foundation for how instructors teach, evaluate, and correct errors.
	•	Helps future instructors understand how students learn.

A.46 - Flight instructor aeronautical knowledge test
	•	A flight instructor must explain material clearly, not just know it personally.
	•	Confirms the applicant is prepared for the instructor-level knowledge exam.
	•	Supports safe teaching of regulations, systems, procedures, and aerodynamics.

A.47 - Flight instructor ground and flight proficiency/practical test
	•	This is about readiness to teach as well as fly.
	•	The applicant must demonstrate instruction skill, analysis, and professional judgment.
	•	Helps ensure future students are trained by someone who can both do and teach.

A.48 - Flight instructor certificate with instrument–(category/class) rating/practical test
	•	Instrument instruction requires a very high standard of precision.
	•	The instructor must teach approaches, holds, scan, procedures, and regulations accurately.
	•	Helps protect students in one of the least forgiving training environments.

A.49 - Spin training
	•	Flight instructors teach stalls and loss-of-control awareness.
	•	Spin training helps them recognize, prevent, and explain spin-related risks.
	•	Supports safer instruction in stall and upset topics.

A.50 - Helicopter Touchdown Autorotation
	•	Autorotation is a critical emergency procedure in helicopters.
	•	Touchdown autorotation requires precise energy and rotor management through landing.
	•	Builds skill for one of the most important power-loss responses in rotorcraft.

A.51 - Fundamentals of instructing knowledge test
	•	Teaching skill still requires formal understanding of how people learn.
	•	Helps future instructors organize lessons, communicate clearly, and correct errors.
	•	Supports safer and more effective instruction.

A.52 - Sport pilot flight instructor aeronautical knowledge test
	•	Sport pilot instructors still carry real instructional responsibility.
	•	Confirms readiness in regulations, privileges, limitations, and teaching knowledge.
	•	Prevents the assumption that simpler aircraft mean simpler teaching standards.

A.53 - Flight instructor with a sport pilot rating flight proficiency check for additional category/class
	•	An added category or class changes what the instructor may teach.
	•	Confirms training and readiness for that expanded authority.
	•	Prevents automatic carryover of teaching privileges without qualification.

A.54 - Flight instructor with a sport pilot rating proficiency check completion endorsement for additional category or class privilege
	•	Creates a record that the added privilege was successfully completed.
	•	Distinguishes between starting training and actually qualifying.
	•	Supports proper documentation of expanded instructional authority.

A.55 - Flight instructor with a sport pilot rating practical test endorsement
	•	Shows the applicant reached practical-test readiness for that instructor certificate.
	•	Serves as the recommending instructor’s formal approval to test.
	•	Helps ensure the examiner receives a qualified applicant.

A.56 - Flight instructor with a sport pilot rating practical test completion endorsement
	•	Documents that the training and proficiency tied to the test were completed.
	•	Supports the certification record for the new authority granted.
	•	Confirms the applicant moved beyond training into qualification.

A.57 - Flight instructor with a sport pilot rating to train sport pilots on flight by reference to instruments
	•	Even limited instrument-reference training can be safety-critical.
	•	Helps ensure the instructor can teach unusual attitude and reference-to-instruments skills correctly.
	•	Prevents unsafe habits from forming in students.

A.58 - Spin training
	•	Gives the applicable instructor candidate a deeper understanding of stall/spin risk.
	•	Supports safer teaching of loss-of-control prevention topics.
	•	Helps instructors recognize and address dangerous student habits early.

A.59 - Ground instructor who does not meet the recent experience requirements
	•	Teaching skill and knowledge can fade when not used.
	•	Helps restore confidence that the instructor is current enough to teach again.
	•	Protects students from outdated or rusty instruction.

A.60 - R-22/R-44 ground training
	•	Robinson helicopters have special handling concerns and SFAR-specific requirements.
	•	Helps cover safety-critical topics like rotor RPM, low-G hazards, and model-specific limits.
	•	Builds the knowledge needed before operating those aircraft.

A.61 - R-22 solo endorsement
	•	Solo in an R-22 requires more than general helicopter training.
	•	Confirms the student was trained specifically in that model before flying alone.
	•	Supports safer solo use in an aircraft with special requirements.

A.62 - R-22 PIC endorsement
	•	Acting as PIC in an R-22 requires model-specific qualification.
	•	Helps ensure the pilot understands the aircraft’s special risks and handling.
	•	Prevents pilots from relying only on general rotorcraft experience.

A.63 - R-22 flight instructor endorsement
	•	Teaching in an R-22 requires deeper model-specific knowledge and judgment.
	•	Helps ensure the instructor can train others safely in that aircraft.
	•	Supports standardization and risk control in Robinson instruction.

A.64 - Flight review in an R-22 helicopter
	•	Keeps proficiency tied to the actual model flown.
	•	Helps refresh handling and safety issues specific to the R-22.
	•	Recognizes that general helicopter currency may not be enough.

A.65 - R-44 solo endorsement
	•	Confirms the student received model-specific training before soloing the R-44.
	•	Helps ensure solo authority matches actual aircraft competence.
	•	Supports safer solo transition into that helicopter.

A.66 - R-44 PIC endorsement
	•	PIC authority in the R-44 requires training beyond general helicopter skill.
	•	Helps the pilot understand model-specific procedures and risks.
	•	Provides a clear record of qualification in that helicopter.

A.67 - R-44 flight instructor endorsement
	•	Teaching in the R-44 requires specific qualification and standardization.
	•	Helps ensure instructors can teach safe procedures in that aircraft.
	•	Reduces the chance of poor model-specific training being passed on.

A.68 - Flight review in an R-44 helicopter
	•	Keeps review and proficiency tied to the model actually operated.
	•	Helps refresh aircraft-specific handling, procedures, and risk awareness.
	•	Supports safer continued operation in the R-44.

A.69 - Completion of a flight review
	•	The flight review is the FAA’s basic periodic proficiency checkpoint for most pilots.
	•	Helps catch drift in skills, procedures, and knowledge before it leads to accidents.
	•	Confirms the pilot can still safely exercise certificate privileges.

A.70 - Completion of any phase of an FAA-sponsored Pilot Proficiency Program (WINGS)
	•	Encourages ongoing training instead of waiting until the last minute for a flight review.
	•	Often provides more frequent practice in safety-critical skills.
	•	Rewards continued proficiency development with a flight review substitute.

A.71 - Completion of an instrument proficiency check (IPC)
	•	Instrument skills are highly perishable when not used regularly.
	•	An IPC restores instrument privileges after a lapse in recent experience.
	•	Helps confirm the pilot can safely return to IFR operations.

A.72 - To act as PIC in a complex airplane
	•	Complex airplanes add systems workload beyond basic flying.
	•	The pilot must manage gear, flaps, and controllable-pitch propeller correctly.
	•	Helps prevent system-management errors that can become safety issues.

A.73 - To act as PIC in a high-performance airplane
	•	More horsepower usually means faster speed, stronger climb, and less time to react.
	•	Transition training helps pilots avoid getting behind the airplane.
	•	Confirms the pilot can manage the added performance safely.

A.74 - To act as PIC in a pressurized aircraft capable of high-altitude operations
	•	High-altitude flying includes oxygen, pressurization, physiology, and emergency-descent issues.
	•	Mistakes at altitude can become life-threatening quickly.
	•	Confirms the pilot was trained for risks not found in basic low-altitude flying.

A.75 - To act as PIC in a tailwheel airplane
	•	Tailwheel airplanes are less forgiving on takeoff and landing roll.
	•	Specific training helps prevent loss of directional control and ground loops.
	•	Confirms the pilot can handle the airplane’s unique ground behavior.

A.76 - To act as PIC of an aircraft in solo operations when the pilot does not hold an appropriate category/class rating
	•	Creates a legal path to gain solo experience toward a new rating.
	•	Keeps those solo operations tied to instructor approval and oversight.
	•	Prevents unsupervised flying outside the pilot’s current certificate privileges.

A.77 - Retesting after failure of a knowledge or practical test
	•	After a failure, the FAA wants proof the weak areas were corrected first.
	•	Helps target added training to the actual deficiencies, not just repeat the test.
	•	Supports a safer and more meaningful retest.

A.78 - Additional aircraft category or class rating (other than ATP)
	•	Adding a category or class means learning new skills, knowledge, or procedures.
	•	Confirms the pilot was trained specifically for that transition.
	•	Provides the core endorsement basis for the added rating process.

A.79 - Type rating only, already holds the appropriate category or class rating (other than ATP)
	•	A type rating is aircraft-specific and often tied to more complex airplanes.
	•	Confirms qualification in that particular aircraft, not just the broader category/class.
	•	Helps document training in systems and procedures unique to that type.

A.80 - Type rating concurrently with an additional category or class rating (other than ATP)
	•	Combines aircraft-specific and broader category/class qualification in one path.
	•	Helps show both training tracks were properly covered.
	•	Prevents gaps when two qualifications are pursued together.

A.81 - Type rating only, already holds the appropriate category or class rating (at the ATP level)
	•	ATP-level type ratings involve advanced aircraft and strict standards.
	•	Clear documentation is important because the privilege is aircraft-specific and significant.
	•	Supports qualification in complex transport-style operations.

A.82 - Type rating concurrently with an additional category or class rating (at the ATP level)
	•	This path combines ATP-level standards with aircraft-specific type qualification.
	•	Helps show the applicant met both sets of requirements together.
	•	Supports accurate documentation for a more complex qualification route.

A.83 - Launch procedures for operating a glider
	•	Glider safety depends heavily on proper launch technique.
	•	Different launch methods create different procedures and hazards.
	•	Confirms the pilot was trained for the launch method actually used.

A.84 - Glider and unpowered ultralight vehicle towing experience
	•	Towing requires specialized skill beyond normal flying.
	•	The tow pilot must manage coordination, stability, and emergencies carefully.
	•	Documents the experience needed before towing others safely.

A.85 - Glider and unpowered ultralight vehicle towing ground and flight
	•	Tow operations require both procedural knowledge and hands-on skill.
	•	Covers signals, emergency actions, aircraft performance, and coordination.
	•	Helps ensure towing is treated as a specialized operation, not ordinary flying.

A.86 - Review of a home-study curriculum
	•	Self-study alone does not prove correct understanding.
	•	Instructor review helps catch misunderstandings before testing or further qualification.
	•	Supports better quality control in home-study-based preparation.

A.87 - Aeronautical experience credit—ultralight vehicles
	•	Recognizes relevant prior experience where the rules allow credit.
	•	Helps avoid unnecessary duplication of training.
	•	Requires documentation so only appropriate experience is counted.

A.88 - Endorsement required for ground training to act as PIC of an aircraft using night vision goggles (NVG)
	•	NVG operations change visual perception, scanning, and risk factors.
	•	Ground training helps the pilot understand limitations, illusions, and equipment use.
	•	Builds knowledge before trying NVG flight operations.

A.89 - Endorsement required for flight training and statement of proficiency to act as PIC of an aircraft using NVG
	•	Classroom knowledge alone is not enough for NVG use.
	•	The pilot must demonstrate real scanning, landing, and obstacle-awareness skill.
	•	Helps ensure actual proficiency in a specialized operation.

A.90 - Endorsement required to provide training for NVGOs
	•	Teaching NVG operations requires a higher level of competence than simply using NVGs.
	•	The instructor must be able to recognize and correct specialized errors.
	•	Protects students in a high-risk training environment.

A.91 - Endorsement for EFVS ground training
	•	EFVS requires both system knowledge and regulatory understanding.
	•	The pilot must know what the system can do, what it cannot do, and when it may be used.
	•	Helps prevent misuse based on misunderstanding the equipment or rules.

A.92 - Endorsement for EFVS flight training
	•	EFVS use in flight requires practice, not just theory.
	•	Helps the pilot learn scan technique, display use, and transition decisions.
	•	Reduces the risk of fixation or poor interpretation during critical phases of flight.

A.93 - Endorsement for EFVS ground and flight training
	•	Documents the full EFVS qualification, not just one part of it.
	•	Confirms the pilot received both rule knowledge and practical training.
	•	Supports safe and legal EFVS operations.

A.94 - Endorsement for EFVS supplementary training
	•	Additional EFVS privileges require added preparation.
	•	Expanded system use usually brings added complexity and decision-making demands.
	•	Helps prevent pilots from using EFVS beyond the level they were trained for.

A.95 - To act as PIC in an aircraft with a simplified flight controls designation
	•	Even with simplified controls, the pilot still needs make-and-model-specific training.
	•	The pilot must understand the aircraft’s features, limits, and any related restrictions.
	•	Prevents overconfidence based only on the word “simplified.”

A.96 - Initial cadre training in an aircraft with simplified flight controls
	•	The initial cadre becomes the foundation for later standardization and training.
	•	Their qualification matters because they help establish safe operating practices in that aircraft.
	•	Supports future instructor, examiner, and pilot development from a solid base.